horrible it was.

00:02:56.780 --> 00:03:02.850
It was in November of 1966, and it
started because of heavy rainfalls

00:03:02.850 --> 00:03:07.120
above Florence that came
down the Arno River and went

00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:09.680
through the center of Florence.

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:15.300
It also flooded close to a third
of the northern part of Italy.

00:03:15.300 --> 00:03:17.280
So Venice was also affected.

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:21.790
It was not just a local disaster,
it was a national disaster of very,

00:03:21.790 --> 00:03:26.320
very large, it was very large.

00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:31.160
Obviously Florence is a cultural
center, and an enormous amount

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:34.730
of cultural resources were damaged.

00:03:34.730 --> 00:03:38.620
3 to 4 million books and
manuscript materials,

00:03:38.620 --> 00:03:42.080
as well as close to
14,000 works of art.

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:44.530
And many of these truly
iconic works of art

00:03:44.530 --> 00:03:49.330
that certainly grab
the world's attention.

00:03:49.330 --> 00:03:51.810
As you can see on the
right, these are pictures

00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:56.370
from a National Geographic
article from 1967 that was,

00:03:56.370 --> 00:04:00.030
it's quite often cited as
a way of the continued,

00:04:00.030 --> 00:04:03.970
people were continually interested
in this and it is quite difficult

00:04:03.970 --> 00:04:08.630
to understand how impactful things
like that article were at the time,

00:04:08.630 --> 00:04:12.240
in a time when we have the
Internet and cable news.

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:17.280
The images of this and the film
were quite important in terms

00:04:17.280 --> 00:04:20.600
of conveying to people
the extent of the damage.

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:26.640
Extremely high waters, very, and
also moving at a very high speed.

00:04:26.640 --> 00:04:29.760
So very destructive,
and full of heating oil.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:36.930
So dirty, moving at great
force, at times over 20 feet.

00:04:36.930 --> 00:04:43.480
This is the following day, the
rain started on November 3,

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:47.200
flooding started in the very
early morning of November 4

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:50.680
