00:38:14.180 --> 00:38:18.700
There are four key components
to that preparedness, response,

00:38:18.700 --> 00:38:21.430
recovery, and mitigation.

00:38:21.430 --> 00:38:24.830
It's important to keep this in
mind, you'll see particularly

00:38:24.830 --> 00:38:29.820
in early preservation, conservation
literature about emergency,

00:38:29.820 --> 00:38:32.610
they'll use one of these
terms, preparedness,

00:38:32.610 --> 00:38:34.880
planning, response, recovery.

00:38:34.880 --> 00:38:36.870
And really what they should be,

00:38:36.870 --> 00:38:40.510
the word they really should be
using is collection emergency risk

00:38:40.510 --> 00:38:43.990
management or heritage
emergency management

00:38:43.990 --> 00:38:46.580
or art emergency management,
but it's a cycle,

00:38:46.580 --> 00:38:50.040
they're all interrelated, you
need to be doing all of them,

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:54.010
you shouldn't be focusing
just on one of them.

00:38:54.010 --> 00:38:56.350
And this is in for
a number of reasons,

00:38:56.350 --> 00:38:59.910
but part of it is a practical one,
emergency managers, our plans,

00:38:59.910 --> 00:39:04.500
our national policies, our
work within this framework,

00:39:04.500 --> 00:39:06.270
and by far the fastest way to think

00:39:06.270 --> 00:39:09.640
about this is to use
medical analogy.

00:39:09.640 --> 00:39:12.540 position:56%
Preparedness are the kinds of things
you do to take care of yourself

00:39:12.540 --> 00:39:15.660
when you're not sick, but to
keep yourself from being sick.

00:39:15.660 --> 00:39:18.810
They could be things like going
to the doctor, having checkups,

00:39:18.810 --> 00:39:22.630
having health insurance,
taking care of yourself.

00:39:22.630 --> 00:39:25.210
Response is what you do when
something happens to you.

00:39:25.210 --> 00:39:27.060
And this is the important
distinction

00:39:27.060 --> 00:39:29.240
between response and recovery.

00:39:29.240 --> 00:39:35.540
When 911, when you call 911,
that's obviously response.

00:39:35.540 --> 00:39:39.400 position:56%
When you start getting treated in
the ambulance going to the hospital,

00:39:39.400 --> 00:39:42.590
and that starts being
recovery to some extent,

00:39:42.590 --> 00:39:45.520
but it clearly is also part
of a response function.

00:39:45.520 --> 00:39:49.290
As you get into recovery,
you're in the emergency room,

00:39:49.290 --> 00:39:52.610
there's more assessment,
there's some triage that's done,

00:39:52.610 --> 00:39:57.570
some assessment, some treatment,
but the goal at that stage

00:39:57.570 --> 00:40:01.040
of the emergency room cycle
is get you stabilized.

00:40:01.040 --> 00:40:04.130
It's not to fully treat you,
it's to get you stabilized.

00:40:04.130 --> 00:40:07.010
You have, you are not going
to get worse, you're alive,

00:40:07.010 --> 00:40:11.070
and now some other doctor,
someone else can take care of you.

00:40:11.070 --> 00:40:12.370
They can move on to other people

00:40:12.370 --> 00:40:15.210
that have life-threatening
situations.

00:40:15.210 --> 00:40:19.450
So a component of recovery is
rehabilitation and it's interesting

00:40:19.450 --> 00:40:21.920
in many early parts of
emergency literature

00:40:21.920 --> 00:40:24.900
in the conservation field,
this notion of recovery

00:40:24.900 --> 00:40:27.450
and rehabilitation is stated.

00:40:27.450 --> 00:40:33.860
But over time, it gets less
priority, it gets less attention,

00:40:33.860 --> 00:40:36.140
and I think that's too bad and
it's one of the things where we're,

00:40:36.140 --> 00:40:38.520
I think that's where
we're focusing on now

00:40:38.520 --> 00:40:41.290
and Florence is an
interesting lesson in all that.

00:40:41.290 --> 00:40:43.940
Recovery can take a long time
