00:47:08.450 --> 00:47:10.780
but we lack structures,
infrastructure,

00:47:10.780 --> 00:47:15.370
and resources to sometimes
do what we know we can do.

00:47:15.370 --> 00:47:18.850
And Katrina really
pointed that out in 2005.

00:47:18.850 --> 00:47:22.110
It really, really, really was
a disaster that was eye-opening

00:47:22.110 --> 00:47:25.720
in the sense of all of the
things that we had done.

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:30.110
It was an eye-opening thing
to see how far short we fell.

00:47:30.110 --> 00:47:36.760
It was an enormously large regional
disaster, it covered many states.

00:47:36.760 --> 00:47:41.240 position:56%
And one of the great American cities
was under close to 80 percent water,

00:47:41.240 --> 00:47:42.880
very similar to Florence.

00:47:42.880 --> 00:47:46.330
And while the cultural impact was
not quite as great as Florence,

00:47:46.330 --> 00:47:48.070
it was certainly significant.

00:47:48.070 --> 00:47:54.400
As was the human cost and the
way in which we responded both

00:47:54.400 --> 00:47:57.480
as a federal government
and as a nation.

00:47:57.480 --> 00:48:02.710
There were a number of things
that came out of the lessons

00:48:02.710 --> 00:48:05.540
from Katrina, and it's one of
I think the the stronger traits

00:48:05.540 --> 00:48:09.630
of American emergency management
in general is we do learn

00:48:09.630 --> 00:48:11.530
from the past, we make changes,

00:48:11.530 --> 00:48:17.960
we attempt to make things
better from what we've learned.

00:48:17.960 --> 00:48:22.690
FEMA had become part
of DHS after 9/11,

00:48:22.690 --> 00:48:26.010
but it was made more
independent after Katrina

00:48:26.010 --> 00:48:31.620
so that it can really focus on
emergency management at large.

00:48:31.620 --> 00:48:35.880
Also some other fundamental things
that happened where response used

00:48:35.880 --> 00:48:38.710
to be at strictly a state
level, and it was hard

00:48:38.710 --> 00:48:40.290
to coordinate across states.

00:48:40.290 --> 00:48:43.320
Now that's allowed, and by far
the most important thing that came

00:48:43.320 --> 00:48:46.490 position:56%
out of Katrina was that public
assistance funding, that's described

00:48:46.490 --> 00:48:49.890
in the Stafford Act, was
extended to cultural institutions.

00:48:49.890 --> 00:48:55.630
That is cultural institutions that
are nonprofits, that need resources

00:48:55.630 --> 00:48:59.190
to start recovery or
to start a response.

00:48:59.190 --> 00:49:02.800
Those have to be applied for,
you don't get those immediately,

00:49:02.800 --> 00:49:05.650
but typically in a
presidential declaration,

00:49:05.650 --> 00:49:07.750
public assistance is one
of the phases and one

00:49:07.750 --> 00:49:09.080
of the things that's authorized.

00:49:09.080 --> 00:49:11.560
And in the past, cultural
institutions generally could not

00:49:11.560 --> 00:49:12.860
apply for that.

00:49:12.860 --> 00:49:14.540 position:56%
It was something that they had to go

00:49:14.540 --> 00:49:17.690
to the small business
administration for support.

00:49:17.690 --> 00:49:21.840
So Katrina and that legislation
did get expanded in a way

00:49:21.840 --> 00:49:26.620
that really did allow for items
that aren't protected in other ways

00:49:26.620 --> 00:49:30.000
to receive some sort of
response in an organized way.

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:33.540
It also showed that just
from the sheer scale,

00:49:33.540 --> 00:49:37.190
that you have less
control, the bigger it is.

00:49:37.190 --> 00:49:40.930
And you need to be as
prepared as you can be

00:49:40.930 --> 00:49:43.430
and do what you can if you can.

00:49:43.430 --> 00:49:45.350
One of the things that also changed

00:49:45.350 --> 00:49:49.330
